<subSubSection id="C32F33C3FF89FF919AB45364FF4CF95A" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8A6048FF89FF919AB45364FD9DFB8C" blockId="4.[160,1156,827,1129]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">
<emphasis id="B941BC5AFF89FF919AB45364FF75FCB1" bold="true" box="[160,229,827,852]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Head.</emphasis>
Labrum expanded laterally, ca. 3.75 times larger than long, with rounded apexes; dorsal surface and anterior margin covered with long and thin setae. Crown of the galealacinia of the maxillae with ca. 16–20 comb-shaped setae. Right mandible with 7–8 fimbriate setae below the inner incisor and ca. 4–5 long, simple and thin setae below the mola. Left mandible with 7–9 fimbriate setae below the inner incisor and ca. 5–6 long simple and thin setae below the mola. Hypopharynx with robust lingua bearing a tuft of small setae, superlinguae densely covered with long and thin setae up to the lower part of the superlinguae. Labium with glossae rhomboid, inner and outer margins clearly concave near apex (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF919B92540EFE74FB8C" box="[390,484,1105,1129]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1310,1333]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1278]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[163,1153,142,1278]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 6. Labial glossa. (a) Thalerosphyrus flowersi (arrow show clearly concave near apex). (b) Thalerosphyrus sinuosus. (c) Thalerosphyrus vietnamensis. (d) Thalerosphyrus thailandensis sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670201" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670201/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 6</figureCitation>
(a)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8A6048FF89FF919AB454C5FEE3FA66" blockId="4.[160,1155,1178,1411]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">
<emphasis id="B941BC5AFF89FF919AB454C5FF6AFB56" bold="true" box="[160,250,1178,1203]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum greatly expanded laterally and posteriorly, and basally fused to the mesonotum (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF919B2E54E1FE04FB33" box="[314,404,1214,1238]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1528]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[163,1153,142,1528]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Thalerosphyrus flowersi (Venkataraman and Sivaramakrishnan, 1987). (a) Habitus in dorsal view. (b) Habitus in ventral view. (c) Detail of abdominal segments VI–IX in ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670189/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(a–b)). Femora with submarginal rows of pointed bristles on the inner and outer margins, increasing in numbers from the fore to the hind leg. Bristles on the dorsal surface of hind femora with subparallel or slightly convergent margin, apex rounded or truncate (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF919B885579FE6BFADB" box="[412,507,1318,1342]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="15.[160,225,877,900]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,845]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[163,1153,142,845]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 7. Bristles on the dorsal face of the hind femur. (a) Thalerosphyrus flowersi. (b) Thalerosphyrus sinuosus. (c) Thalerosphyrus vietnamensis. (d) Thalerosphyrus thailandensis sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670203/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 7</figureCitation>
(a)). Hind tibia with one row of thin setae and a row of 7–11 arrow-shaped bristles in marginal and submarginal position. Tarsal claw with 3–4 teeth (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF919AF85534FED9FA66" box="[236,329,1387,1411]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="16.[160,225,945,968]" captionTargetBox="[163,1152,142,913]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[163,1153,142,913]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 9. Tarsal claw. (a) Thalerosphyrus flowersi. (b) Thalerosphyrus sinuosus. (c) Thalerosphyrus vietnamensis. (d) Thalerosphyrus thailandensis sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670207/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 9</figureCitation>
(a)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8A6048FF89FF919AB455EBFF4CF95A" blockId="4.[160,1155,1460,1727]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">
<emphasis id="B941BC5AFF89FF919AB455EBFE89FA28" bold="true" box="[160,281,1460,1485]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Posterolateral expansion not developed on segment I, weakly developed on segment II, strongly developed on segment III and increasing in size up to VIII and subparallel to the body (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF919BD755A5FD8DF9F7" box="[451,541,1530,1554]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="5.[160,225,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[163,1153,142,1528]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[163,1153,142,1528]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 1. Thalerosphyrus flowersi (Venkataraman and Sivaramakrishnan, 1987). (a) Habitus in dorsal view. (b) Habitus in ventral view. (c) Detail of abdominal segments VI–IX in ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670189/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 1</figureCitation>
(c)). Gill I with asymmetrical elongated and rounded plate, 1.5 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF9198275642FD0FF9D0" box="[563,671,1565,1589]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="17.[160,225,916,939]" captionTargetBox="[162,1152,142,885]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[162,1153,142,885]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 10. Gill I. (a) Thalerosphyrus flowersi. (b) Thalerosphyrus sinuosus. (c) Thalerosphyrus vietnamensis. (d) Thalerosphyrus thailandensis sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670209" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670209/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 10</figureCitation>
(a)). Gill 
<collectionCode id="ED24F88DFF89FF9199155642FC8BF9D1" box="[769,795,1564,1589]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">II–</collectionCode>
<collectionCode id="ED24F88DFF89FF91990F5642FCA0F9D0" box="[795,816,1565,1589]" country="Norway" name="Mykotektet, National Veterinary Institute" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">VI</collectionCode>
strongly asymmetrical, wider than long. Gill VII oval and almost symmetrical. Posterior margin of tergites with irregularly pointed teeth and numerous row of microdenticle rows (
<figureCitation id="130E7CCDFF89FF9199B9563DFB87F99F" box="[941,1047,1634,1658]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="17.[159,224,1732,1755]" captionTargetBox="[161,1151,1035,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[161,1151,1035,1701]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figure 11. Posterior margin of the abdominal tergite IV. (a) Thalerosphyrus flowersi. (arrow show numerous row of microdenticles). (b) Thalerosphyrus sinuosus. (c) Thalerosphyrus vietnamensis. (d) Thalerosphyrus thailandensis sp. nov. (arrow show a few row of microdenticles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3670211" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3670211/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1494">Figure 11</figureCitation>
(a)). Cerci whitish in the proximal part, with 3–4 dark brown bands increasing in size towards the apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
